<doc id="1970" url="https://en.wikinews.org/wiki?curid=1970" title="2004 Commonwealth Judo Championships">
<h1>2004 Commonwealth Judo Championships</h1>
&lt;strong class="published"&gt;&lt;span id="publishDate" class="value-title" title=""&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span class="Z3988" style="display:none" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rfr_id=rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:User%3ADendodge&amp;rft_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:&amp;rft.atitle=2004%20Commonwealth%20Judo%20Championships&amp;rft.jtitle=Wikinews&amp;rft.date=&amp;rft.aucorp=Wikinews+contributors&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.rights=CC-BY+2.5&amp;rft.identifier=&amp;rft.artnum="&gt; &lt;/span&gt; 

&lt;a href="w%3AAuckland"&gt;AUCKLAND&lt;/a&gt; – This event saw an emergence of the Pacific Island nations into the Commonwealth Judo community. For many years only &lt;a href="Fiji"&gt;Fiji&lt;/a&gt;'s Nacanieli Takayawa was apparent on the international scene. Although not taking many medals, the efforts going into development in nations such as &lt;a href="Tonga"&gt;Tonga&lt;/a&gt; allowed many of their players to place 5th or 7th. &lt;a href="India"&gt;India&lt;/a&gt; also performed well, especially their women's team.

♡❤♡2004 Commonwealth Judo Championships♡❤♡

♡❤13-14 November 2004, &lt;a href="w%3AAuckland"&gt;Auckland&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="New%20Zealand"&gt;New Zealand&lt;/a&gt;♡❤

♡❤♡Mens -60&amp;nbsp;kg♡❤♡
<ol>
BULLET::::1. Chana, Navjot (&lt;a href="India"&gt;IND&lt;/a&gt;)
BULLET::::2. Smith, Tom (&lt;a href="England"&gt;ENG&lt;/a&gt;)
BULLET::::3. Boore, Stephen (&lt;a href="Wales"&gt;WAL&lt;/a&gt;)
BULLET::::4. &lt;li value="3"&gt;Leat, Alister (&lt;a href="New%20Zealand"&gt;NZL&lt;/a&gt;)

