<doc id="2962" url="https://en.wikinews.org/wiki?curid=2962" title="News Briefs: January 9, 2005">
<h1>News Briefs: January 9, 2005</h1>
&lt;strong class="published"&gt;&lt;span id="publishDate" class="value-title" title=""&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span class="Z3988" style="display:none" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rfr_id=rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:User%3ADendodge&amp;rft_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:&amp;rft.atitle=News%20Briefs%3A%20January%209%2C%202005&amp;rft.jtitle=Wikinews&amp;rft.date=&amp;rft.aucorp=Wikinews+contributors&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.rights=CC-BY+2.5&amp;rft.identifier=&amp;rft.artnum="&gt; &lt;/span&gt; 

The following were among the stories were making international headlines :

<h3>U.S. soldier sentenced for abusing Iraqis</h3>
Sgt. 1st Class Tracy Perkins was given a six-month jail sentence as the result of two incidents a year ago where Iraqi captives were pushed into the Tigris River. He also admitted to lying to investigators when questioned about the incident.

<h3>Generation of warfare in Sudan ends</h3>
The longest war in Africa's history came to a close after Sudanese Vice President Ali Osman Taha and John Garang, leader of rebel fighters, signed a peace accord. The accord did not include the separate conflict in western Darfur.

<h3>Pentagon mulls use of Special Forces death squads in Iraq</h3>
A Newsweek report claims that U.S. military leaders are considering a Reagan-era "Salvador option" &amp;mdash; the use of Special Forces soldiers for assassinations in Iraq. The idea would be to eliminate rebel leadership in an attempt to shorten the war. 


